one time I was a kid.

01:15:57.820 --> 01:16:01.889
I had this friend,
Todd moray.

01:16:01.891 --> 01:16:04.158
I remember his dad was always
out of work and on welfare,

01:16:04.160 --> 01:16:06.327
but he had this job once,

01:16:06.329 --> 01:16:09.630
where he worked at this
place called Saxon shoes.

01:16:09.632 --> 01:16:11.098
It was a shoe store downtown

01:16:11.100 --> 01:16:12.934
where they used to take
an X-ray of your foot

01:16:12.936 --> 01:16:15.670
to determine the shoe size.

01:16:15.672 --> 01:16:17.471
One summer Todd and i
are down by the creek

01:16:17.473 --> 01:16:20.241
next to the houses
where we lived.

01:16:20.243 --> 01:16:23.177
We found this pair
of box turtles.

01:16:23.179 --> 01:16:26.247
One was a little bit
lighter than the other.

01:16:26.249 --> 01:16:30.818
And Todd had the idea that
we'd take these things as pets.

01:16:30.820 --> 01:16:32.420
Which meant we had
to choose our favorites.

01:16:32.422 --> 01:16:35.289
And I remember Todd ran for
the bigger, darker one,

01:16:35.291 --> 01:16:38.259
which we assumed was male.

01:16:38.261 --> 01:16:40.528
And I got the smaller,
lighter one,

01:16:40.530 --> 01:16:43.698
which we assumed was female.

01:16:43.700 --> 01:16:48.803
He called his boxo
and I called mine boxie.

01:16:48.805 --> 01:16:51.539
Later that day we
took out our pocket knives

01:16:51.541 --> 01:16:55.509
and carved markings
into their backs.

01:16:55.511 --> 01:17:01.282
He carved out an o
and I carved out an x.

01:17:01.284 --> 01:17:03.217
It wasn't even
to tell 'em apart.

01:17:03.219 --> 01:17:06.187
I mean, it was easy because
of the color of their shell.

01:17:07.889 --> 01:17:11.292
This was to tell the universe
that they were ours.

01:17:12.894 --> 01:17:17.365
So we built them these,
these big cardboard houses

01:17:17.367 --> 01:17:21.969
that we stuffed full of mulch
and dirt and grass clippings.

01:17:21.971 --> 01:17:26.073
And we fed them
caterpillars and slugs,

01:17:26.075 --> 01:17:28.209
and lettuce and carrots.

01:17:28.211 --> 01:17:30.578
And when we could
we'd meet at this common area

01:17:30.580 --> 01:17:32.079
in between our rows of houses

01:17:32.081 --> 01:17:34.715
and takes them
for walks on leashes.

01:17:34.717 --> 01:17:35.983
But it was never very orderly

01:17:35.985 --> 01:17:37.585
because one of them
would go straight

01:17:37.587 --> 01:17:40.054
and the other one
would walk in a circle.

01:17:40.056 --> 01:17:42.723
Or vice versa.

01:17:42.725 --> 01:17:44.659
By the end of the summer
my parents told me

01:17:44.661 --> 01:17:46.994
I had to get rid of my turtle.

01:17:46.996 --> 01:17:50.931
To them it wasn't a pet,
it was a wild animal.

01:17:50.933 --> 01:17:53.067
But I'd really grown
to like the thing.

01:17:53.069 --> 01:17:55.102
I'm sure boxie didn't
feel the same way about it,

01:17:55.104 --> 01:17:56.270
but I was eight.

01:17:56.272 --> 01:17:57.738
It's a selfish age.

01:17:57.740 --> 01:17:59.740
So my parents set a deadline.

01:17:59.742 --> 01:18:02.777
I had to get rid of the turtle
the day before school.

01:18:02.779 --> 01:18:06.614
And I remember I waited
'til the very last second.

01:18:06.616 --> 01:18:09.116
On labor day.

01:18:11.119 --> 01:18:13.054
There were dark clouds
in the sky

01:18:13.056 --> 01:18:14.622
and you could feel
the pressure dropping

01:18:14.624 --> 01:18:16.757
right before a big storm.

01:18:16.759 --> 01:18:20.461
But my dad was insistent.

01:18:20.463 --> 01:18:24.298
So I took boxie out to the
creek where I found her,

01:18:24.300 --> 01:18:26.801
and I let her go.

01:18:26.803 --> 01:18:28.969
And every time Todd and I would
go back there we'd look for her

01:18:28.971 --> 01:18:32.273
but I never found her.

01:18:32.275 --> 01:18:34.875
Figured the storm got her.

